{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775881655678,"sessionID":"ses_28535b1d1ffe8kVL495I7tmRwR","part":{"id":"prt_d7acb955c001lQFmpc8MY75Vqc","messageID":"msg_d7acb8ca3001nfAmpS3sqzSzDR","sessionID":"ses_28535b1d1ffe8kVL495I7tmRwR","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-e3142f3558104ac7b4298b80350dc845","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/manifests/charts/agentcube/README.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/manifests/charts/agentcube/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AgentCube Helm Chart\n2: \n3: [![Artifact Hub](https://img.shields.io/endpoint?url=https://artifacthub.io/badge/repository/agentcube/agentcube)](https://artifacthub.io/packages/helm/agentcube/agentcube)\n4: \n5: Helm chart for AgentCube platform - Kubernetes-native AI agent runtime and code interpreter.\n6: \n7: ## Introduction\n8: \n9: This chart bootstraps an [AgentCube](https://github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube) deployment on a [Kubernetes](http://kubernetes.io) cluster using the [Helm](https://helm.sh) package manager.\n10: \n11: ## Prerequisites\n12: \n13: - Kubernetes 1.20+\n14: - Helm 3.0+\n15: - PV provisioner support in the underlying infrastructure\n16: \n17: ## Installing the Chart\n18: \n19: To install the chart with the release name `agentcube`:\n20: \n21: ```bash\n22: helm install agentcube ./agentcube --namespace agentcube --create-namespace\n23: ```\n24: \n25: The command deploys AgentCube on the Kubernetes cluster in the default configuration.\n26: \n27: ## Uninstalling the Chart\n28: \n29: To uninstall/delete the `agentcube` deployment:\n30: \n31: ```bash\n32: helm uninstall agentcube --namespace agentcube\n33: ```\n34: \n35: The command removes all the Kubernetes components associated with the chart and deletes the release.\n36: \n37: ## Configuration\n38: \n39: The following table lists the configurable parameters of the AgentCube chart and their default values.\n40: \n41: | Parameter | Description | Default |\n42: |-----------|-------------|---------|\n43: | `global.imageRegistry` | Global Docker image registry | `\"\"` |\n44: | `global.imagePullSecrets` | Global image pull secrets | `[]` |\n45: | `global.namespaceOverride` | Override namespace | `agentcube` |\n46: | `controllerManager.enabled` | Enable Controller Manager | `true` |\n47: | `controllerManager.replicaCount` | Controller Manager replicas | `2` |\n48: | `controllerManager.image.repository` | Controller Manager image repository | `agentcube/controller-manager` |\n49: | `controllerManager.image.tag` | Controller Manager image tag | `v1.0.0` |\n50: | `controllerManager.image.pullPolicy` | Controller Manager image pull policy | `IfNotPresent` |\n51: | `controllerManager.resources` | Controller Manager resource requests/limits | See values.yaml |\n52: | `workloadManager.enabled` | Enable Workload Manager | `true` |\n53: | `workloadManager.replicaCount` | Workload Manager replicas | `2` |\n54: | `workloadManager.image.repository` | Workload Manager image repository | `agentcube/workload-manager` |\n55: | `workloadManager.image.tag` | Workload Manager image tag | `v1.0.0` |\n56: | `workloadManager.image.pullPolicy` | Workload Manager image pull policy | `IfNotPresent` |\n57: | `workloadManager.resources` | Workload Manager resource requests/limits | See values.yaml |\n58: | `router.enabled` | Enable Router | `true` |\n59: | `router.replicaCount` | Router replicas | `3` |\n60: | `router.image.repository` | Router image repository | `agentcube/router` |\n61: | `router.image.tag` | Router image tag | `v1.0.0` |\n62: | `router.image.pullPolicy` | Router image pull policy | `IfNotPresent` |\n63: | `router.service.type` | Router service type | `ClusterIP` |\n64: | `router.service.port` | Router service port | `8080` |\n65: | `router.resources` | Router resource requests/limits | See values.yaml |\n66: | `rbac.create` | Create RBAC resources | `true` |\n67: | `redis.addr` | Redis server address | `\"\"` (required) |\n68: | `redis.password` | Redis password | `\"\"` |\n69: | `monitoring.enabled` | Enable monitoring | `false` |\n70: | `monitoring.serviceMonitor.enabled` | Enable ServiceMonitor | `false` |\n71: \n72: Specify each parameter using the `--set key=value[,key=value]` argument to `helm install`. For example:\n73: \n74: ```bash\n75: helm install agentcube ./agentcube \\\n76:   --namespace agentcube \\\n77:   --set controllerManager.replicaCount=3 \\\n78:   --set redis.addr=redis:6379\n79: ```\n80: \n81: Alternatively, a YAML file that specifies the values for the above parameters can be provided while installing the chart. For example:\n82: \n83: ```bash\n84: helm install agentcube ./agentcube -f custom-values.yaml\n85: ```\n86: \n87: ## Production Deployment\n88: \n89: For production deployments, use the production values file:\n90: \n91: ```bash\n92: helm install agentcube ./agentcube \\\n93:   --namespace agentcube \\\n94:   --create-namespace \\\n95:   -f values-prod.yaml\n96: ```\n97: \n98: ## Development Deployment\n99: \n100: For development deployments, use the development values file:\n101: \n102: ```bash\n103: helm install agentcube ./agentcube \\\n104:   --namespace agentcube-dev \\\n105:   --create-namespace \\\n106:   -f values-dev.yaml\n107: ```\n108: \n109: ## Upgrading\n110: \n111: To upgrade an existing deployment:\n112: \n113: ```bash\n114: helm upgrade agentcube ./agentcube \\\n115:   --namespace agentcube \\\n116:   --reuse-values\n117: ```\n118: \n119: ## Rollback\n120: \n121: To rollback to a previous revision:\n122: \n123: ```bash\n124: helm rollback agentcube <revision> --namespace agentcube\n125: ```\n126: \n127: ## Redis Configuration\n128: \n129: The AgentCube platform requires a Redis instance. Configure it using:\n130: \n131: ```bash\n132: helm install agentcube ./agentcube \\\n133:   --namespace agentcube \\\n134:   --create-namespace \\\n135:   --set redis.addr=redis:6379 \\\n136:   --set redis.password=your-password\n137: ```\n138: \n139: ## Monitoring\n140: \n141: To enable Prometheus monitoring:\n142: \n143: ```bash\n144: helm install agentcube ./agentcube \\\n145:   --namespace agentcube \\\n146:   --create-namespace \\\n147:   --set monitoring.enabled=true \\\n148:   --set monitoring.serviceMonitor.enabled=true\n149: ```\n150: \n151: ## Ingress\n152: \n153: To expose the Router via Ingress:\n154: \n155: ```bash\n156: helm install agentcube ./agentcube \\\n157:   --namespace agentcube \\\n158:   --create-namespace \\\n159:   --set ingress.enabled=true \\\n160:   --set ingress.hosts[0].host=agentcube.example.com\n161: ```\n162: \n163: ## High Availability\n164: \n165: For high availability deployments:\n166: \n167: 1. Set replica counts to 3 or more\n168: 2. Enable PodDisruptionBudgets\n169: 3. Configure pod anti-affinity rules\n170: 4. Use LoadBalancer service type for Router\n171: \n172: ## RBAC\n173: \n174: The chart creates the following RBAC resources:\n175: - ServiceAccounts for each component\n176: - ClusterRole for Workload Manager\n177: - ClusterRoleBinding for Workload Manager\n178: - Role and RoleBinding for Router (optional)\n179: \n180: ## Security\n181: \n182: The chart applies the following security best practices:\n183: - Non-root user (UID 1000)\n184: - Read-only root filesystem\n185: - Dropped Linux capabilities\n186: - Security contexts for pods and containers\n187: - Minimal RBAC permissions\n188: \n189: ## Troubleshooting\n190: \n191: ### Check deployment status:\n192: \n193: ```bash\n194: kubectl get pods --namespace agentcube\n195: kubectl get services --namespace agentcube\n196: ```\n197: \n198: ### View logs:\n199: \n200: ```bash\n201: kubectl logs -n agentcube -l app.kubernetes.io/name=agentcube,app.kubernetes.io/component=controller-manager\n202: kubectl logs -n agentcube -l app.kubernetes.io/name=agentcube,app.kubernetes.io/component=workload-manager\n203: kubectl logs -n agentcube -l app.kubernetes.io/name=agentcube,app.kubernetes.io/component=router\n204: ```\n205: \n206: ### Check CRDs:\n207: \n208: ```bash\n209: kubectl get crds | grep agentcube\n210: kubectl get agentruntimes -n agentcube\n211: kubectl get codeinterpreters -n agentcube\n212: ```\n213: \n214: ## License\n215: \n216: Apache-2.0\n217: \n218: ## Support\n219: \n220: For issues and questions:\n221: - GitHub Issues: https://github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/issues\n\n(End of file - total 221 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AgentCube Helm Chart\n\n[![Artifact Hub](https://img.shields.io/endpoint?url=https://artifacthub.io/badge/repository/agentcube/agentcube)](https://artifacthub.io/packages/helm/agentcube/agentcube)\n\nHelm chart for AgentCube platform - Kubernetes-native AI agent runtime and code interpreter.\n\n## Introduction\n\nThis chart bootstraps an [AgentCube](https://github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube) deployment on a [Kubernetes](http://kubernetes.io) cluster using the [Helm](https://helm.sh) package manager.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n- Kubernetes 1.20+\n- Helm 3.0+\n- PV provisioner support in the underlying infrastructure\n\n## Installing the Chart\n\nTo install the chart with the release name `agentcube`:\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/manifests/charts/agentcube/README.md","time":{"start":1775881655668,"end":1775881655676}}}}
